         <abstract>
            <p>The reviewer of the collection of essay called<italic>The Cambridge Companion to John Updike</italic>, edited by Stacey Olster, confesses that in the middle years of the career of John Updike, he lost interest in the author's novels for the paradoxical reasons that he felt they were either too predictable, seemingly too programmatic or too unpredictable, Updike pumping up a flagging imagination with an assortment of<italic>outré</italic>forms and subjects. But the reviewer rejoices that the predominantly fine essays in the<italic>Companion</italic>—by scholars such as D. Quentin Miller, Sanford Pinsker, Edward Vargo, Donald J. Greiner, and John N. Duvall—renewed his interest in the works unread, prompted him to do much catching up, and left him wondering, more ruefully than ever, upon Updike's death in January of 2009 why the novelist had never won a highly deserved Nobel Prize for Literature.</p>
         </abstract>
